00:00:21.922 --> 00:00:23.380
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So now we

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:26.740
resume after our hiatus
in the introductory theme,

00:00:26.740 --> 00:00:28.240
because of the snow day.

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:31.360
We resume the
introductory theme, right?

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:34.510
And this is the second of
three introductory lectures.

00:00:34.510 --> 00:00:37.710
And today we deal with the
modal characteristics and role.

00:00:37.710 --> 00:00:40.900
So we talk about the different
modes of public transportation

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.350
and their characteristics
and what role they play.

00:00:44.350 --> 00:00:46.600
We're looking at the range
of modes and services,

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:48.040
the descriptions of each mode.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:52.600
And we'll do some comparisons
in terms of how they perform.

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:55.180
So what are the
roles for each mode?

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:57.910
When we think about the
different modes that

00:00:57.910 --> 00:01:00.372
can be used for
transportation, we

00:01:00.372 --> 00:01:02.870
can think in
different dimensions.

00:01:02.870 --> 00:01:07.240
And one of them is going from
low density to high density.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:10.450
That is from very
sparse OD matrices

00:01:10.450 --> 00:01:12.970
where origins and
destinations are

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:17.830
both scattered in a geographical
area to a situation where,

00:01:17.830 --> 00:01:21.700
along a particular corridor,
there are concentrated origin

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:24.310
destination pairs and
many people wanting

00:01:24.310 --> 00:01:26.980
to travel along the corridor.

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:28.540
Obviously this
happens more in cities

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:30.830
than it happens in rural areas.

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:34.060
And we also see
that we can think

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:37.390
about it in that same dimension
from having low vehicle

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:40.630
capacity being necessary
to requiring high vehicle

00:01:40.630 --> 00:01:41.420
capacity.

00:01:41.420 --> 00:01:43.990
And by capacity, I
mean the capacity

00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:46.150
of a vehicle to hold
passengers inside, right?

00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:52.440
So in that direction, we have
private modes on the top.

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:56.320
And we have public modes,
so-called public at the bottom.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:59.220
So we all know what the auto is.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:02.620
It's a private mode that is
often used a single person,

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.620
sometimes by a family.

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:11.470
And yeah, so very low density
of the payer being served.

00:02:11.470 --> 00:02:14.140
Then you go to
carpool where people

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:16.090
are more in that same vehicle.

00:02:16.090 --> 00:02:18.920
And there might be multiple
stops along the way.

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:21.320
And vanpool, slightly
larger vehicle.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:24.370
This is often private.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:28.330
So it could be arrangements
between co-workers

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:32.050
requiring capacity
higher than a normal car.

00:02:32.050 --> 00:02:33.010
So they get a van.

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:36.700
And maybe one of them drives
it or maybe they hire a driver.

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.180
So then in the public
side we have taxi.

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:42.370
And I'm using the
term here generally.

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:46.780
So you can think of
this as one of the newer

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:48.760
forms of taxi of
transportation that were

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:52.180
companies like Uber and Lyft.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:56.830
So you might hail a
cab just for yourself.

00:02:56.830 --> 00:02:58.000
And that's the extreme.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Or you might use
the pool servicing,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.440
the pool services offered
by those companies,

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:03.910
or you might share a taxi.

00:03:03.910 --> 00:03:08.244
So you start increasing the
utilization of that vehicle.

00:03:08.244 --> 00:03:09.160
Then we have publicos.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:12.490
Publicos are-- they
can be cars or vans.

00:03:12.490 --> 00:03:17.890
They're operated by a private
driver often in an association.

00:03:17.890 --> 00:03:22.240
And they usually
drive these vehicles

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:27.550
along more semi-flexible,
semi-fixed corridors.

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:30.040
So people more or less
know the routes they serve.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:32.120
They have some flexibility.

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:35.010
So they can say,
well, can you take me,

00:03:35.010 --> 00:03:36.220
you know, around the corner.

00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:37.240
And they'll do that.

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:43.210
So it's the mode that is sort of
right before formalized public

00:03:43.210 --> 00:03:44.230
transportation.

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:45.550
Then we have fixed route bus.

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:48.190
That's the route
one and the buses

00:03:48.190 --> 00:03:51.550
here in Boston and in many
places, traditional bus

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:52.420
service.

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:54.910
BRT, which is bus
rapid transit, which

00:03:54.910 --> 00:04:00.160
is a mode where buses are being
used to deliver transit that

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:03.130
is generally delivered
via rail services,

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:05.090
light rail services
in particular.

00:04:05.090 --> 00:04:07.590
We'll look at some examples
later in this lecture.

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:11.290
And then we have light rail
like Boston's Green Line

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:15.220
and heavy rail, which is the
traditional subway or Metro

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:16.570
system, right?

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:19.089
In the middle sometimes
subscription bus.

00:04:19.089 --> 00:04:23.140
So the car services
that are sometimes--

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:29.550
it's oft-- like a
normal sized bus.

00:04:29.550 --> 00:04:33.380
It could be paid
for by a company

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:35.720
to get its employees
to the site, right?

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:37.520
So it's somewhere in the middle.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:38.540
Because it's not public.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:40.800
So not everybody can use it.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:42.530
But it's not private.

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:44.660
Because somebody
else, so there's

00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:46.700
a third party who is
providing the service.

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:53.610
So along that same direction
of increasing vehicle

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:55.680
capacity and passenger flows.

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:59.610
We can also look at what happens
to the operating arrangements.

00:04:59.610 --> 00:05:02.310
And we have three operating
arrangements listed here,

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:03.510
three classes.

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:04.590
What happens to drivers?

00:05:04.590 --> 00:05:06.030
What happens to right-of-way?

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:08.730
What happens to
routing and scheduling?

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:12.600
So how much does it
cost to have drivers

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:15.050
operating a private car?

00:05:15.050 --> 00:05:17.460
If it's just you, you
don't think about the cost,

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:20.040
although you could assume some
cost for your value of time.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:25.590
But you're not paying
someone to drive you often.

00:05:25.590 --> 00:05:27.670
As you move to van,
as I said earlier,

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:30.060
if it's an arrangement where
you or one of your friends

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:32.340
is the one driving the
van that's free as well.

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:37.680
Or if you hire a driver, then
it becomes a low cost salary

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:40.410
or payment for that
driving service.

00:05:40.410 --> 00:05:42.540
Then we have mini bus and bus.

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:44.820
So depending on the
size of the system

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:48.330
and how big the vehicles
are and the context of how

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:52.260
that driver gets hired,
it could be low cost.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:57.000
But as [INAUDIBLE]
and labor unions,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.730
then the cost starts
increasing, right?

00:05:58.730 --> 00:06:02.730
So you have higher
salaries, and especially

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:04.920
as you move towards light
rail and heavy rail,

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:07.510
much higher salaries
for drivers.

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:10.740
However, when we get to heavy
rail, especially the more

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:12.600
modern, the most
advanced systems

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:14.550
of heavy rail, a lot of
these are driverless.

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:16.200
They operate automatically.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:18.240
And they might have
attendants inside of them.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:20.700
But they don't necessarily
need to have attendants.

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:23.520
So you could think
in the extreme,

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:25.140
this is coming
back down to, well,

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:26.580
it's a robot
driving the vehicle.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:29.650
And I don't have to
pay for a driver.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:33.610
In terms of right-of-way, we
start with shared right-of-way,

00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:36.910
so cars, vans, minibuses, and
buses typically share the road

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:37.930
with other cars, right?

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:39.800
So they're sharing the space.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:42.940
And they're stuck in
traffic, if there is traffic.

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:46.660
For bus, light rail,
you have a mix.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:49.930
Some of these systems
can operate only

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:54.040
in a shared right-of-way or
only in dedicated corridors

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:55.300
or a mix of both.

00:06:55.300 --> 00:06:59.260
So light rail systems, for
example, often have shared--

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:00.899
often have dedicated
right-of-ways,

00:07:00.899 --> 00:07:02.440
but when they hit
intersections, they

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:04.660
have to wait like
all the other cars

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.662
to cross the intersection,
not always, but often.

00:07:07.662 --> 00:07:09.370
And then there's
dedicated right-of-ways,

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:13.840
which is more typical for Metro
systems where it's a tunnel

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:17.530
or it's a grade or
it's up and over, yeah,

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:20.710
like an elevated section.

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:23.440
But it's dedicated
to this Metro system.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:25.750
So you have a question,
[AUDIENCE],, yeah?

00:07:25.750 --> 00:07:28.220
AUDIENCE: Yeah, now, light rail.

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:31.120
What would you call light
rail on certain segments

00:07:31.120 --> 00:07:32.020
that needs--

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:34.045
that has its own
complete right-of-way

00:07:34.045 --> 00:07:35.290
it's grade separated?

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:36.440
Because they have that--

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:38.930
these big systems where
they're partially light rail

00:07:38.930 --> 00:07:40.830
and they're
partially segregated,

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:43.149
and even that heavy
rail that even has

00:07:43.149 --> 00:07:44.440
occasional crossing [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:45.200
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That's right, yeah, yeah.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:46.075
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:46.075 --> 00:07:47.616
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Absolutely.

00:07:47.616 --> 00:07:48.920
And that's a great question.

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.300
So the question is
why, or how do we

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:57.137
label some services that
share characteristics

00:07:57.137 --> 00:07:57.970
that I'm describing.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.790
I'm seeing Metro as this way
and light rail as this way.

00:08:00.790 --> 00:08:04.120
But there are, in fact,
systems that combines

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:05.510
some of these characteristics.

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:08.320
So I'm talking about the
stereotypical descriptions

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:09.620
of each system.

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:11.290
And one of the points
of this lecture

00:08:11.290 --> 00:08:14.410
is, in fact, that it's blurry.

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:15.620
All these lines are blurry.

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:19.040
And you can combine
different characteristics.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:20.470
So, yeah.

00:08:20.470 --> 00:08:22.517
But it's still
useful as a framework

00:08:22.517 --> 00:08:24.100
to think about all
the different modes

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:27.706
and their typical or
stereotypical characteristics.

00:08:27.706 --> 00:08:31.400
Right, so, routing
and scheduling,

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:34.990
so if you're in your own car,
it's fully flexible, right?

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:39.140
You decide where the car is,
when it leaves, when it ends,

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:40.690
its trip.

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:42.669
As you move towards
minibus and you're

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:44.434
sharing the ride
with other people,

00:08:44.434 --> 00:08:47.500
it might have either fixed
routes or fully flexible

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:51.160
or somewhere in between, like
the Publicos that I described

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:53.590
where there is a
semi-fixed route

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:55.900
but with some
flexibility to deviate

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:59.530
from those to accommodate
certain passenger's

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:00.820
destinations.

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:03.760
And then as we move to
the most formal systems,

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:06.040
it's a picked through--
it's a published service

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:08.890
plan with stops
at certain places

00:09:08.890 --> 00:09:12.430
and people know
where to go take it.

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:15.109
Any questions on the
terms of services?

00:09:15.109 --> 00:09:15.734
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:09:15.734 --> 00:09:16.182
[INAUDIBLE]

00:09:16.182 --> 00:09:16.910
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
[INAUDIBLE],, yes?

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:17.740
AUDIENCE: On Publicos.

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:18.990
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:21.210
AUDIENCE: Typically the
flexibility would be,

00:09:21.210 --> 00:09:22.650
would be with the alighting.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:23.900
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:25.530
AUDIENCE: You would have
to know where to board.

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:25.810
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That's right.

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:28.110
AUDIENCE: But they could
drop you off anyplace.

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:29.360
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:31.320
Sometimes you can
call the companies.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:34.410
And they can communicate and
say, arrange for a pickup.

00:09:34.410 --> 00:09:37.184
But most typically, yeah,
you have more flexibility

00:09:37.184 --> 00:09:38.100
on the alighting side.

00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:42.220
All right.

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:42.929
Other categories.

00:09:42.929 --> 00:09:44.220
Let's talk about rights-of-way.

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:45.670
We started talking about that.

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:47.380
So degree of segregation.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:50.110
We can think about
three different levels,

00:09:50.110 --> 00:09:52.000
surface with mixed traffic.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.120
This is typical for
buses or light rail that

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:56.800
has no preferential treatment.

00:09:56.800 --> 00:09:58.810
Then we go to
longitudinal separation

00:09:58.810 --> 00:10:00.790
with at-grade crossing.

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:03.920
Well, the Green Line here in
Boston is mostly like that,

00:10:03.920 --> 00:10:05.170
several benches are like that.

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:07.240
So they run on their own track.

00:10:07.240 --> 00:10:08.950
When they hit an
intersection, they

00:10:08.950 --> 00:10:12.310
have to wait for the red
light with other cars.

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:15.160
Some sections of the
Green Line are actually

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:16.840
surface with mixed traffic.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:20.740
I'm thinking about the
last end of the E line.

00:10:20.740 --> 00:10:22.570
And then full separation, right?

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:25.090
So that could be at-grade
tunnel, elevated.

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:25.810
Technologies.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:28.330
Let's talk about technologies.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:31.690
Support, which is referring
to contact between the vehicle

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:34.180
on the surface, what
counters the force of gravity

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:36.070
essentially for these vehicles.

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:39.430
We have rubber tire
on concrete for buses.

00:10:39.430 --> 00:10:41.290
That's typically what it is.

00:10:41.290 --> 00:10:42.520
Some trains have that.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:45.400
If you go through the Metro
system in Paris, for example,

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:50.170
you'll see rubber tire on
concrete for their Metro.

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:53.890
That has a benefit over steel
wheel on steel rail in terms

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:56.680
of the grip, and,
therefore, acceleration

00:10:56.680 --> 00:10:58.270
and braking distances.

00:10:58.270 --> 00:10:59.680
They can be shorter.

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:02.890
Steel wheel and steel rail is
more common for rail systems.

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:05.470
And the maintenance
cost is lower.

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:07.670
And they last longer.

00:11:07.670 --> 00:11:11.510
But they have a lower
coefficient of friction.

00:11:11.510 --> 00:11:13.900
So braking distances are longer.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:18.977
And the capacity to climb
very steep grades is reduced.

00:11:18.977 --> 00:11:19.810
You have a question?

00:11:19.810 --> 00:11:24.290
AUDIENCE: Yeah, do you
think Paris [INAUDIBLE]

