AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:47.755
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That's right, yeah.

00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:54.940
OK, so we talked about
automatic train protection.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.000
Here's how it works.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.150
This is the classical
block system for rails.

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:02.050
And here's how we control
the longitudinal movement

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:03.950
in a system like the red line.

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:06.460
So this is the
fixed block system.

00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:10.420
What you do is that you divide
the track into sections.

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:13.930
And the goal of the system
is to prevent trains

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:15.290
from colliding into each other.

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:19.120
So let's suppose that there's a
train right here and in maroon.

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:22.030
And it's occupying
a section of track.

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:24.900
The track knows that a train
is occupying that segment.

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:30.280
And to prevent a
collision, it blocks trains

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:32.530
from entering the
previous segment.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:33.700
OK?

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:35.360
And how does it do that?

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:39.160
It does that by setting the
speed limit on the segment

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:41.890
to [INAUDIBLE] upstream to 0.

00:18:41.890 --> 00:18:45.090
So if a train were to
enter that segment,

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:48.300
it would be braked
automatically.

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:51.090
And then the speed
limit gets increased

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:52.230
as you go farther upstream.

00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:55.080
So a train can move
along the track.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:59.630
But if it gets too close
to the piece of track

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:02.430
to being occupied, it will
have to slow down or brake.

00:19:02.430 --> 00:19:05.940
Have you been on a train
here or elsewhere where

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.520
you're braked all of
a sudden in the middle

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:10.993
of the track between stations?

00:19:10.993 --> 00:19:14.070
Yeah, and then normally you
hear the brakes going off.

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:15.790
And then it starts again.

00:19:15.790 --> 00:19:17.880
So what happens in those
cases is that the driver

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:19.410
exceeded the speed limit.

00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:22.080
And the automatic train
protection system kicked in.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:24.570
It brakes, it brings
the train to a halt.

00:19:24.570 --> 00:19:27.180
And the driver won't be able
to start the train again

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:31.510
until the pressure on the
brake system is released.

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:32.290
Questions?

