00:19:58.440 --> 00:19:58.520
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:19:58.520 --> 00:19:59.050
AUDIENCE: There was like--

00:19:59.050 --> 00:20:00.550
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, so--

00:20:00.550 --> 00:20:03.381
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] years
ago the DC Metro [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:03.381 --> 00:20:04.880
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
All right,

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:08.630
so, one of the things with
block systems like this

00:20:08.630 --> 00:20:10.760
is that they constrain
the capacity of the line.

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:12.950
If we look at the red
line, in particular,

00:20:12.950 --> 00:20:16.370
this is the line that
puts a constraint

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:20.500
on the frequency of service.

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:21.830
Approximately three minutes.

00:20:21.830 --> 00:20:23.740
You can't run service
more often than that.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:27.230
And the red line, because
of this, the way the blocks

00:20:27.230 --> 00:20:28.280
were assigned.

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:29.480
So what happens?

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:33.350
As you're moving from
Kendall to Charles MGH,

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:37.070
and particularly in the
segments from MGH to Park,

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:39.780
this segment right here
is downhill, right?

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:44.600
You're going from elevated
downhill to subway.

00:20:44.600 --> 00:20:49.490
So you're also going downhill
on steel wheel on steel rail.

00:20:49.490 --> 00:20:51.020
And the track may be wet.

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:52.470
Because it was outside.

00:20:52.470 --> 00:20:54.560
So there's a concern
that the braking distance

00:20:54.560 --> 00:20:56.270
might be quite long.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:59.840
And to be very safe and
conservative, what happens

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:02.070
is that trains are
not allowed to enter

00:21:02.070 --> 00:21:04.130
Park Street until
the train ahead

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:05.630
departs Downtown Crossing.

00:21:05.630 --> 00:21:08.330
So you need to clear the
platform of Downtown Crossing.

00:21:08.330 --> 00:21:12.620
And only then can you start
moving into Park Street.

00:21:12.620 --> 00:21:17.520
So that might cause trains to
be held up at Charles actually.

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:18.410
So, yeah.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:24.300
So if we look at the time that
it takes the train to close in,

00:21:24.300 --> 00:21:28.230
that is from the beginning
when the head of the train

00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:34.830
hits the circuit just after
Charles MGH to the time it

00:21:34.830 --> 00:21:37.210
actually gets to
Park Street and opens

00:21:37.210 --> 00:21:41.670
it's doors, the dwell time at
Park Street serving passengers,

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:43.884
allowing passengers to
get off and to board.

00:21:43.884 --> 00:21:45.300
And then you have
the running time

00:21:45.300 --> 00:21:47.910
between Park Street
and Downtown Crossing.

00:21:47.910 --> 00:21:49.980
And finally the time
it requires a train

00:21:49.980 --> 00:21:54.180
to close its doors and exit
and for the tail of the train

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:56.580
to clear the circuit so that
it's no longer occupying

00:21:56.580 --> 00:21:57.150
the circuit.

00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:58.350
That's about three minutes.

00:21:58.350 --> 00:22:00.430
You can't run service
more often than not.

00:22:00.430 --> 00:22:03.460
So you would have to change
the blocking, the sign

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:05.850
of this segment to the
red line if you wanted

00:22:05.850 --> 00:22:09.240
to increase the frequency.

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:14.160
More modern systems are
indications based train control

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:15.270
systems.

00:22:15.270 --> 00:22:17.370
And what happens
in those cases is

00:22:17.370 --> 00:22:18.810
that the blocks are not fixed.

00:22:18.810 --> 00:22:20.940
They move between vehicles.

00:22:20.940 --> 00:22:24.060
A computer will look at the
speeds and the distances

00:22:24.060 --> 00:22:26.970
between trains and
generate virtual blocks

00:22:26.970 --> 00:22:28.680
that are quite short.

00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:31.620
And they can control
with finer precision

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:34.725
how the speed limits
that a train has that

00:22:34.725 --> 00:22:36.720
are being applied for safety.

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:40.140
Often, these are in systems that
are automatically controlled.

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:42.540
So you have the
moving block system,

00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:44.640
which increases the capacity.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:47.670
And you have a computer
also regulating

00:22:47.670 --> 00:22:50.640
the speed, which eliminates
driver variability

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:54.640
and further increases the
capacity of the system.

