and it is not changing
and you wait 60 seconds,

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:57.140
you can proceed through.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:23:59.806
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Right,
and you have to proceed slowly.

00:23:59.806 --> 00:24:00.710
But, yeah.

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:01.280
Right.

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:05.540
So they allow trains to
sometimes to both two trains

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:07.790
to birth on a platform
in some cases,

00:24:07.790 --> 00:24:11.090
although they're not
really liking that anymore.

00:24:11.090 --> 00:24:13.160
But they used it
a little bit more.

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:13.890
Right, so--

00:24:13.890 --> 00:24:14.570
AUDIENCE: And in
Chicago, though,

00:24:14.570 --> 00:24:16.542
that train's
[INAUDIBLE] you can call

00:24:16.542 --> 00:24:19.179
to get clearance to pull past
the red signal [INAUDIBLE]..

00:24:19.179 --> 00:24:21.470
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That's true for most systems.

00:24:21.470 --> 00:24:22.370
You can override.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:27.530
And with a very slow speed you
can take control and manually--

00:24:27.530 --> 00:24:30.080
and you need that, because
sometimes these systems fail.

00:24:30.080 --> 00:24:31.269
And they all go red.

00:24:31.269 --> 00:24:32.810
So you still have
to move the trains.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:34.640
And you need this
override system.

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:36.670
But it won't allow
quick movement.

00:24:36.670 --> 00:24:39.440
AUDIENCE: That's how we had
runaway train on Red Line.

00:24:39.440 --> 00:24:40.690
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yep.

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:41.240
OK.

00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:44.810
The next level of automation
is manually setting the speed

00:24:44.810 --> 00:24:46.637
below the maximum level.

00:24:46.637 --> 00:24:48.470
That's the Red Line,
what he just described.

00:24:48.470 --> 00:24:52.570
In-cab signals, the speed limit
of the block that the train is

00:24:52.570 --> 00:24:55.880
occupying is sent to the
cab so that the driver

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:57.680
knows what the speed limit is.

00:24:57.680 --> 00:25:00.350
It's up to the driver to
determine what the speed is.

00:25:00.350 --> 00:25:03.020
But if the driver
exceeds that speed,

00:25:03.020 --> 00:25:04.640
the automatic train
protection system

00:25:04.640 --> 00:25:08.270
kicks in and brakes the
train to a halt. All right?

00:25:08.270 --> 00:25:11.420
Then we have manual setting
of dwell times only.

00:25:11.420 --> 00:25:15.230
So the train drives
itself between stations.

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:18.980
The driver decides on
the door opening and door

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:21.140
closing manually and,
therefore, controls how long

00:25:21.140 --> 00:25:23.000
the doors are open for.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.690
So it's a more advanced
system from the '70s and '80s.

00:25:26.690 --> 00:25:31.130
And then we have
semi-automated so we

00:25:31.130 --> 00:25:34.640
have automatic train supervision
or automatic train regulation.

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:36.200
A good example of
this is Tren Urbano

00:25:36.200 --> 00:25:39.950
in San Juan, Puerto Rico
and the London Underground

00:25:39.950 --> 00:25:41.370
central line.

00:25:41.370 --> 00:25:45.800
So here the train can
drive itself automatically

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:47.600
between stations.

00:25:47.600 --> 00:25:50.330
The driver only pushes
a button to tell

00:25:50.330 --> 00:25:54.260
the train go to the next
station essentially.

00:25:54.260 --> 00:25:56.480
In Tren Urbano's
case, and I imagine

00:25:56.480 --> 00:25:58.690
this is true in all system.

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:00.560
The drivers are
required to manually

00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:05.620
operate for small fraction
of their [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:05.620 --> 00:26:08.110
to manually control
trains if there

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:10.594
is a failure of the system Eli?

00:26:10.594 --> 00:26:14.380
AUDIENCE: But they don't
control dwell times in these?

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:16.590
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
They can but often not.

00:26:16.590 --> 00:26:19.480
Often the dwell times
are also regulated.

00:26:19.480 --> 00:26:23.510
AUDIENCE: They
definitely control them

00:26:23.510 --> 00:26:24.600
on the Central Line.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:25.100
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, so--

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:25.430
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] Warning
for the people on the platform.

00:26:25.430 --> 00:26:25.660
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:26.690
AUDIENCE: --people
on the platform.

00:26:26.690 --> 00:26:28.310
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So you have this button

00:26:28.310 --> 00:26:30.680
that you push, the driver,
to sort of authorize

00:26:30.680 --> 00:26:31.640
the movement forward.

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:35.060
So you can, right,
you can not press it

00:26:35.060 --> 00:26:38.580
and thereby extend
the dwell time.

00:26:38.580 --> 00:26:42.440
But the speed between the
stations and everything else

00:26:42.440 --> 00:26:44.440
is the parking of the
train at the platform

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:45.648
and the opening of the doors.

00:26:45.648 --> 00:26:47.270
It all happens automatically.

00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:48.520
Then you have full automation.

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:51.400
And this comes often
with a communications

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:53.120
based train control.

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:58.830
So you could drive this
without any driver inside.

00:26:58.830 --> 00:27:02.860
Shut-- airport trains
are often like this.

00:27:02.860 --> 00:27:06.040
But we're seeing this in
Metro systems as well.

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:11.840
In some systems, they
still have attendants

00:27:11.840 --> 00:27:14.960
or they still have a
driver just in case

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:19.100
or for political reasons.

00:27:19.100 --> 00:27:22.010
But these systems
can drive themselves.

00:27:22.010 --> 00:27:24.500
You often need
platform screen doors.

00:27:24.500 --> 00:27:27.860
That's one of the concerns
with fully automatic systems.

00:27:27.860 --> 00:27:31.065
It allows people to
go into the track

00:27:31.065 --> 00:27:32.690
and the computer
won't see them, right?

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:38.840
So it has to be a more
controlled system.

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:42.900
Line 14 in Paris is
another example of that.

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:45.950
Yeah, and then you can
[INAUDIBLE] capacity

00:27:45.950 --> 00:27:47.310
through a moving block system.

00:27:47.310 --> 00:27:52.670
And here's an example of
the C Line in New York City.

00:27:52.670 --> 00:27:53.170
Questions?

00:27:53.170 --> 00:27:56.830
AUDIENCE: You said
[INAUDIBLE] people [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:56.830 --> 00:27:58.830
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, so these systems

00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:00.526
have platform screen
doors and they

00:28:00.526 --> 00:28:01.650
don't have a driver, right?

00:28:01.650 --> 00:28:03.990
So you go in and they
move between stations.

00:28:03.990 --> 00:28:06.660
But you also have
lots of Metro systems

00:28:06.660 --> 00:28:08.910
in cities that work like that.

00:28:08.910 --> 00:28:13.770
As of 2013, there were 48
fully automated Metro lines

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:18.060
in 32 cities over the world
that didn't require a driver

00:28:18.060 --> 00:28:18.634
to operate.

00:28:18.634 --> 00:28:19.800
And that number is going up.

