AUDIENCE: Low floor is better
for wheelchair accessibility.

00:29:18.350 --> 00:29:18.890
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Uh-huh, there's

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:19.556
another benefit.

00:29:19.556 --> 00:29:21.170
So one of the
benefits of low floor

00:29:21.170 --> 00:29:22.994
is wheelchair accessibility.

00:29:22.994 --> 00:29:23.660
Another benefit?

00:29:23.660 --> 00:29:24.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:24.860
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Sorry?

00:29:24.860 --> 00:29:26.444
AUDIENCE: The boarcding
time is lower.

00:29:26.444 --> 00:29:28.651
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Shorter dwell times, right?

00:29:28.651 --> 00:29:31.190
These people are not climbing
stairs to get on the vehicle

00:29:31.190 --> 00:29:32.330
or off the vehicle.

00:29:32.330 --> 00:29:34.699
You can speed up the process
and increase capacity.

00:29:34.699 --> 00:29:35.240
Another idea?

00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:37.120
AUDIENCE: The ride
is more stable?

00:29:37.120 --> 00:29:38.453
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Sorry?

00:29:38.453 --> 00:29:39.950
AUDIENCE: The ride
is more stable.

00:29:39.950 --> 00:29:42.241
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
I'm not sure that's the case.

00:29:42.241 --> 00:29:45.220
I don't think that has
a large impact on--

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:49.890
yeah, on-- I don't think vehicle
design in terms of high floor

00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:52.680
or low floor increases
stability that much, not

00:29:52.680 --> 00:29:56.040
anyway for the speeds
at which these buses go.

00:29:56.040 --> 00:29:59.450
It's not much of a
critical consideration.

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:00.900
OK, right-of-way.

00:30:00.900 --> 00:30:02.440
So all options are available.

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:06.330
You could be on the street
sharing your lane with cars.

00:30:06.330 --> 00:30:08.400
Or you could have a
dedicated bus lane

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:11.790
with no signals and
preferential treatment

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:14.640
if you have some signals.

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:16.260
So everything goes.

00:30:16.260 --> 00:30:19.980
In terms of guidance,
often it is manual.

00:30:19.980 --> 00:30:22.770
But sometimes you
have the systems

00:30:22.770 --> 00:30:24.870
to automatically guide the bus.

00:30:24.870 --> 00:30:28.500
And we'll see two examples of
that later in this lecture.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:29.197
Propulsion.

00:30:29.197 --> 00:30:30.280
All options are available.

00:30:30.280 --> 00:30:30.900
You have electric.

00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:31.566
You have diesel.

00:30:31.566 --> 00:30:34.830
You have hybrid, everything.

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:38.100
And in terms of fare
payment, another key decision

00:30:38.100 --> 00:30:41.340
if you're thinking of a
new bus system in your city

00:30:41.340 --> 00:30:43.290
is, do you have
the people paying

00:30:43.290 --> 00:30:45.900
the fare as they
get on the vehicle

00:30:45.900 --> 00:30:48.120
or do you want that to--

00:30:48.120 --> 00:30:50.580
do you want that payment
to happen outside?

00:30:50.580 --> 00:30:54.060
So are you going to make
some stations where people

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:56.130
pay their fare and then
board without having

00:30:56.130 --> 00:30:57.960
to interact with a fare box?

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:00.520
The benefit of the latter
is that you speed up

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:01.500
the dwell times.

00:31:01.500 --> 00:31:03.120
But of course, you
need to spend more

00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:07.740
on fare gates or some other
means of paying a fare.

00:31:10.590 --> 00:31:13.635
AUDIENCE: Is there a benefit
to high floor for urban buses?

