00:46:34.790 --> 00:46:35.289
Right.

00:46:35.289 --> 00:46:40.664
OK, so AC power, well,
you can change the voltage

00:46:40.664 --> 00:46:41.580
on the current, right?

00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:43.260
So you can make it
very high voltage.

00:46:43.260 --> 00:46:46.830
And that means that it's easy
and cheaper to transmit over

00:46:46.830 --> 00:46:48.060
longer distances.

00:46:48.060 --> 00:46:50.460
So whenever you have
intercity trains,

00:46:50.460 --> 00:46:57.120
almost always they will be
overhead high voltage AC.

00:46:57.120 --> 00:47:01.200
For subways, shorter
distances, tunnels,

00:47:01.200 --> 00:47:04.320
you don't want to have
transformers everywhere.

00:47:04.320 --> 00:47:06.810
And the other problem
with high voltage

00:47:06.810 --> 00:47:10.980
is that it arcs more easily
between two pieces of metal.

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:15.000
So in a subway sys-- in
a subway train like this,

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:19.680
you don't have much space
between underneath the train

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:22.870
to fit things in with
proper electrical isolation.

00:47:22.870 --> 00:47:26.640
So if it's an intercity
train, it's higher floor.

00:47:26.640 --> 00:47:28.080
You have more space.

00:47:28.080 --> 00:47:31.240
But if it's a Metro system,
often you have less space.

00:47:31.240 --> 00:47:37.230
So if it's DC inside
the train and you

00:47:37.230 --> 00:47:40.890
don't need transformers
[INAUDIBLE]

00:47:40.890 --> 00:47:43.740
at very short intervals
in your system.

00:47:43.740 --> 00:47:46.830
Yeah, so that was a
short parenthesis.

00:47:46.830 --> 00:47:49.260
Commuter rail is another
kind of rail system.

00:47:49.260 --> 00:47:50.940
So the stereotypical
description.

00:47:50.940 --> 00:47:53.950
Vehicles operating in trains
with long station spacing.

00:47:53.950 --> 00:47:56.610
This frequently.

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:59.050
Serving long trips
into the central city.

00:47:59.050 --> 00:48:01.710
There's usually a large
balance between peak hour

00:48:01.710 --> 00:48:04.250
and off-peak service.

00:48:04.250 --> 00:48:08.760
So commuter rail to bring
people into work in the morning

00:48:08.760 --> 00:48:13.350
and out of work [INAUDIBLE]
in [INAUDIBLE] afternoon.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:16.350
So you often have
service every hour

00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:18.720
or every two hours in
the middle of the day.

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:22.680
It's on the sign for
frequent service.

00:48:22.680 --> 00:48:24.210
Your key decision--
the decisions

00:48:24.210 --> 00:48:26.800
are fare collection strategies.

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:28.750
Are you going to put
gates on the whole system

00:48:28.750 --> 00:48:30.590
as if it were a Metro system?

00:48:30.590 --> 00:48:32.800
Are you going to
have paper tickets?

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:36.610
Some systems are moving
towards mobile phone ticketing

00:48:36.610 --> 00:48:40.150
where you buy something
that flashes in colors

00:48:40.150 --> 00:48:43.210
and proves that you've
bought a valid pass.

00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:46.920
So different strategies
for fare collection.

00:48:46.920 --> 00:48:50.040
Line length, how long-- how
far out from the city center

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:53.100
are you going to lay
track and provide service?

00:48:53.100 --> 00:48:55.060
Are you going to through
route in the CBD?

00:48:55.060 --> 00:48:58.020
That is, is the train going
to only get to the CBD

00:48:58.020 --> 00:48:59.070
and turn back?

00:48:59.070 --> 00:49:01.050
Or are you going
to cross the city

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:05.460
and provide service
on the other side

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:07.860
having crossed the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:09.240
That's pretty critical actually.

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:13.020
Because it's commuter
rail is very directional.

00:49:13.020 --> 00:49:17.010
So if you don't have
a place near the city

00:49:17.010 --> 00:49:19.530
to store your trains after
you have inbound service,

00:49:19.530 --> 00:49:22.060
you'd have to then
take them out.

00:49:22.060 --> 00:49:25.820
So you're running trips that
cost you money to operate,

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:27.307
and we're not
serving many trips.

00:49:27.307 --> 00:49:28.890
So if you have through
routing and you

00:49:28.890 --> 00:49:32.500
have a yard close
to the city center,

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:35.690
it might make more sense.

00:49:35.690 --> 00:49:39.920
Station spacing is another issue
and extent of parking capacity.

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:40.730
Why parking?

00:49:40.730 --> 00:49:46.580
Because commuter rail is often
accessed with a park and ride

00:49:46.580 --> 00:49:47.520
service, right?

00:49:47.520 --> 00:49:51.260
So you're usually-- you drive
to a commuter rail station.

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:52.520
You park there.

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:54.200
And then you take
the commuter rail.

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:58.755
Questions on commuter rail?

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:04.180
OK.

00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:05.070
Some examples.

00:50:05.070 --> 00:50:08.850
[INAUDIBLE] this
[INAUDIBLE] diesel.

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:12.290
So in some sections
it runs on diesel.

00:50:12.290 --> 00:50:17.800
As it gets closer to the city
center, it uses electric power.

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:20.170
Here's Mumbai.

00:50:20.170 --> 00:50:21.850
This one has a catenary.

00:50:21.850 --> 00:50:25.932
So it's taking power
from these catenaries.

00:50:25.932 --> 00:50:27.795
This is GO Transit in Toronto.

00:50:30.510 --> 00:50:34.149
This is typical of commuter rail
having two levels, two decks,

00:50:34.149 --> 00:50:34.940
fit more people in.

00:50:39.370 --> 00:50:40.550
OK.

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:44.070
So what are the traditional
service concepts?

00:50:44.070 --> 00:50:45.990
Bus on shared right of way.

00:50:45.990 --> 00:50:50.300
Street car or let's say light
rail on a shared right-of-way.

00:50:50.300 --> 00:50:52.430
Heavy rail on
exclusive right of way.

00:50:52.430 --> 00:50:55.100
And then commuter or
regional rail on something

00:50:55.100 --> 00:50:58.250
that is semi-exclusive or
exclusive right of way.

00:50:58.250 --> 00:51:03.460
Sometimes commuter rail shares
the segments with freight.

00:51:03.460 --> 00:51:07.560
So-- and that's
it's semi-exclusive.

00:51:07.560 --> 00:51:09.610
Newer service concepts, BRT.

00:51:09.610 --> 00:51:14.800
So we're looking at using
buses to operate something that

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:19.840
is more akin to light
rail or even to lighter

00:51:19.840 --> 00:51:22.390
heavy rail, if you want.

00:51:22.390 --> 00:51:26.020
So including exclusive lanes
and or transit signal priority

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:30.520
where the signals turn green
when one of these vehicles

00:51:30.520 --> 00:51:34.255
approaches to not delay
the vehicle [INAUDIBLE]..

00:51:34.255 --> 00:51:36.820
And then light rail on
exclusive right-of-way,

00:51:36.820 --> 00:51:38.725
which makes it more
like heavy rail

00:51:38.725 --> 00:51:41.350
if you look at the stereotypical
descriptions that we had here.

00:51:46.460 --> 00:51:46.960
OK.

00:51:46.960 --> 00:51:48.085
And what else is happening?

00:51:48.085 --> 00:51:49.580
Increasing diversity.

00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:51.320
Driver arrangements.

00:51:51.320 --> 00:51:57.130
Instead of having people hiring
part-timers to cover the peaks

00:51:57.130 --> 00:52:01.890
or having 10-hour days
but not five days a week.

00:52:01.890 --> 00:52:04.960
And then payment by
vehicle type so you

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:09.850
as much for [INAUDIBLE]
for a heavy rail car as you

00:52:09.850 --> 00:52:11.020
would for a bus.

00:52:11.020 --> 00:52:14.050
So let's go back to
part-timers and 10-hour days.

00:52:14.050 --> 00:52:17.300
Why are these
[INAUDIBLE] help increase

00:52:17.300 --> 00:52:19.850
the efficiency,
[INAUDIBLE] efficiency,

00:52:19.850 --> 00:52:23.940
of a bus or a rail system?

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:25.128
Why is that necessary?

00:52:28.620 --> 00:52:31.230
AUDIENCE: Like as people that
just work in a peak period

00:52:31.230 --> 00:52:32.250
where you need more--

00:52:32.250 --> 00:52:34.260
if you're operating
more of your fleet

00:52:34.260 --> 00:52:36.510
but if you don't actually
need them for the whole day.

00:52:36.510 --> 00:52:36.900
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: OK.

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:38.640
So that would be for
part-timers, right?

00:52:38.640 --> 00:52:39.140
AUDIENCE: Yeah, part-timers.

00:52:39.140 --> 00:52:39.750
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, so you

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:42.870
might need more to run more
service only at the peaks.

00:52:42.870 --> 00:52:44.430
And the peaks are
not long enough.

00:52:44.430 --> 00:52:47.772
They're also not--
they're also not spaced--

00:52:47.772 --> 00:52:49.980
they're kind of spaced eight
hours apart aren't they?

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:51.930
So an eight-hour
day doesn't really

00:52:51.930 --> 00:52:53.700
work to cover both peaks.

00:52:53.700 --> 00:52:57.120
So that's why you can do
that by hiring part-timers

00:52:57.120 --> 00:53:01.080
or by extending the day to get
10 hours and cover both peaks.

00:53:04.270 --> 00:53:04.770
OK.

00:53:04.770 --> 00:53:05.760
Routing and scheduling.

00:53:05.760 --> 00:53:10.790
So fixed, flexible,
advanced booking.

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:13.530
Yeah, so vehicle types.

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:18.180
We have all these minibuses,
articulated buses, rail cars,

00:53:18.180 --> 00:53:19.860
bi-level rail cars, low floor.

00:53:19.860 --> 00:53:21.510
We saw some examples.

00:53:21.510 --> 00:53:22.445
Control options.

00:53:22.445 --> 00:53:23.820
Traditionally it
was fixed block.

00:53:23.820 --> 00:53:25.490
But now we have moving block.

00:53:25.490 --> 00:53:27.660
And we have fancier
systems [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:27.660 --> 00:53:29.460
collisions and to
actually control

00:53:29.460 --> 00:53:34.410
the system to run faster
and more even headway.

00:53:34.410 --> 00:53:36.320
And you have dual
mode operations.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:39.690
So bus systems or
light rail systems

00:53:39.690 --> 00:53:43.380
that work more like
buses but also more like

00:53:43.380 --> 00:53:44.980
rails in some segments.

00:53:44.980 --> 00:53:49.950
So in some cases, this dual
mode has more to do with power.

00:53:49.950 --> 00:53:54.390
So it could be a bus that runs
electric in a tunnel section

00:53:54.390 --> 00:53:57.570
but runs diesel [INAUDIBLE]
tunnel section like the Silver

00:53:57.570 --> 00:53:59.775
Line here in Boston.

00:53:59.775 --> 00:54:02.370
It could be having some
sort of [INAUDIBLE] system

00:54:02.370 --> 00:54:06.810
that operates on streets as
a normal bus would but then

00:54:06.810 --> 00:54:11.280
enters a corridor where it's
fully dedicated to the bus

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:12.090
system.

00:54:12.090 --> 00:54:14.340
So it's operating
in both manners.

00:54:14.340 --> 00:54:14.960
Yeah?

